## Combining Selectors {.smaller}

Selectors can be combined: 
- each selector produces a **set** of columns
- **set operations** (`&`, `|`, `^`, `-`, `~`) can be used
to combine selectors
- column names or lists of columns can be used directly

```{.python}
# Inverse: NOT numeric
~s.numeric()

# OR: datetime columns OR string columns
s.any_date() | s.string()

# AND: string columns without nulls
s.string() & ~s.has_nulls()

# XOR: either string, or name starts with "date_" but not both
s.string() ^ s.glob("date_*")

# Include: string columns OR col "date"
s.string() | "date"

# Exclude: all columns except "datetime-col"
s.all() - "datetime-col"

```


::: {.notes}
df = pd.DataFrame({"a": ["a", "b"], "date_1": [2024, 2025], "date_str": ["Monday", "Tuesday"]})
:::

## Extracting Selected Columns

Get the list of selected columns:

::: {#a0b75cb7 .cell execution_count=8}
``` {.python .cell-code}
df = pd.DataFrame(
    {
        "age": [25, 30, 35],
        "name": ["Alice", None, "Charlie"],
        "city": ["NYC", "LA", "Chicago"],
    }
)

selector = s.has_nulls()
columns_with_nulls = selector.expand(df)

# Use in dataframe operations: capitalize columns with nulls
df[columns_with_nulls].apply(lambda x : x.str.upper())
```

